The search radius precondition is not checked:
pythonradius = args.radius   # default 6
There is no assertion that r >= max_displacement / 4 before the correlation is computed. As discussed, this is a silent failure mode. One line would close it:
pythonassert radius >= expected_max_displacement / 4, \
    "Search radius too small — true matches fall outside window"


Part 1 — Visualizing whether the three things are learned
Each of the three claims needs a different visualization:

Claim 1 — Motion-sensitive local features
The question is: do features respond differently to different motions?
Visualization: Feature Response Map

for each motion type (left, right, up, down):
    take a frame pair
    compute C_t[p, :] at every p
    compute the peak displacement at each p:
        peak(p) = argmax over q of C_t[p, q]
    
    draw on image:
        color = displacement direction at p
        brightness = confidence (max score at p)

→  save as  motion_response_{left,right,up,down}.png

Expected pattern:
    left translation  →  uniform rightward arrows
    right translation →  uniform leftward arrows
    deeper regions    →  shorter arrows
    shallow regions   →  longer arrows

Claim 2 — Temporal correspondence
The question is: does the model find the correct match across frames?
Visualization: Correspondence Map

pick N random positions p in frame t
for each p:
    find best match q* = argmax over q of C_t[p, q]
    draw line from p in frame t to q* in frame t+1

→  save as  correspondence_overlay.png

Expected pattern:
    lines should be parallel and consistent
    line length should vary with depth
    (shallow points → long lines,
     deep points    → short lines)

Claim 3 — Spatial relations / geometric layout
The question is: does the displacement field have geometric structure consistent with the camera model?
Visualization: Depth-from-Displacement Map

given a frame pair with known translation direction:
    at each position p:
        mu(p) = expected displacement from C_t[p, :]
        Z_hat(p) = fx * tau_x / mu_x(p)   ← recovered depth

    draw Z_hat as a heatmap over the image

→  save as  recovered_depth_map.png

compare side by side with:
    ground truth depth map

Expected pattern:
    recovered depth should correlate with ground truth
    especially at ball center where the signal is clear

Part 2 — Full image depth decoding for downstream use
Two levels to test:

Level A — direct geometric recovery (no learning)
    given frozen encoder + both frames + known tau:
        C_t = correlation(Z_t, Z_t+1)
        for each p:
            mu(p) = sum_q a(p,q) * (q-p)   soft displacement
            Z_hat(p) = fx * tau_x / (mu_x(p) * 4)
                                      ↑
                              factor 4 for downsampling
        upsample Z_hat to original resolution
    
    → no probe training needed
    → purely geometric
    → tests claim 2 directly

Level B — learned depth decoder (for downstream)
    freeze encoder
    for each p in full image:
        feat = C_t[p, :]
    train a small decoder:
        input:  C_t  [H', W', (2r+1)^2]
        output: depth map  [H', W', 1]
        architecture: two 1x1 conv layers + upsample
        loss: L1 on normalized depth
    
    → this is the downstream-ready model
    → tests whether full spatial depth is decodable

Concrete output layout
output/
├── motion_response/
│   ├── left.png          ← claim 1
│   ├── right.png
│   ├── up.png
│   └── down.png
│
├── correspondence/
│   └── overlay.png       ← claim 2
│
├── depth_recovery/
│   ├── geometric.png     ← claim 3, level A
│   └── gt_comparison.png
│
└── depth_decoder/
    ├── pred_depth.png    ← level B, downstream
    ├── gt_depth.png
    └── error_map.png

Key distinction between Level A and Level B
Level A:  Z_hat(p) = fx * tau_x / mu_x(p)
          purely geometric, no training
          only valid for left/right translation
          proves the displacement field is geometrically correct

Level B:  depth decoder trained on C_t
          learns the mapping
          generalizes across motion types
          ready for depth4control downstream use
Level A is the honest scientific test — it proves the geometry is there without any additional learning. Level B is the practical test — it proves the representation is usable for a real downstream task.
